Cover each of the {= evidence_facet =} closed public-evidence facets below. For each facet, supply public source-backed rows for at least {= supplier =}+ South Africa bakery, baked-goods, confectionery, frozen or par-baked, biscuit, cake, donut, chocolate, patisserie, specialty bakery, bakery-ingredient, retail-fresh bakery, or closely related suppliers, with at least {= url =}+ URL for each facet/supplier pair.

The supplier may be a company, trading name, brand, division, operating bakery or manufacturer, ingredient supplier, or site-qualified supplier when the cited source is site-specific. Suppliers may repeat across facets when the source evidence supports separate roles, but a supplier does not need to appear in all three facets. `category_product` is the direct product/category grounding facet; use `food_safety_certification` and `retail_presence` rows only when the cited page explicitly supports that declared role. Every row, including certification and retail rows, must still identify the supplier and visibly ground it in South Africa and an in-scope bakery/confectionery/ingredient activity. A `.co.za` domain or South African-looking URL can reinforce other evidence, but it is not enough by itself for South Africa grounding.

Evidence facets are the {= facet_count =} closed labels below:
- `category_product`: concrete product-line, product-family, ingredient-form, formulation/application, manufacturing-line, or production-capability evidence from a supplier-controlled official page, brand/division page, product/range page, facility/capability page, or supplier-hosted product specification. The page must name specific products, product families, ingredient forms, applications, or production capabilities tied to the submitted supplier. Certifier pages, certificate PDFs, certification directories, business directories, trade profiles, retailer pages, broad parent/investor pages, and generic homepages that only say the supplier serves the bakery/food/retail industry are not enough for this facet.
- `food_safety_certification`: active/current certification evidence tied to the supplier, site, or product range. Use a supplier-hosted certificate, food-safety/quality policy page, certification page, certifier-issued certificate page/PDF, or supplier-specific certification directory entry whose visible text names the scheme/program/status and gives site, scope, or product-range context. Generic register/search pages, generic quality claims, incidental footer badges, product pages with passing accreditation mentions, broad homepages, retailer text, broad investor text, business directories, and trade profiles are not enough. Withdrawn, suspended, expired, or status-unclear certificates do not satisfy this facet when that status is visible.
- `retail_presence`: named external channel relationship evidence. The page must name at least one external retailer, stockist, distributor, wholesaler, foodservice customer, corporate customer, collaboration partner, or private-label/manufacturer counterparty and state the supplier's relationship to that counterparty. Supplier/parent pages, retailer corporate pages, stockist pages, filings, or reputable trade sources can qualify when they name the external counterparty. Generic "retail", "retail section", "major retail chains", "retail packaging", own stores, own cafes, franchise/store locators, factory shops open to the public, tenant/review pages, ecommerce product availability, and retailer SKU pages are not enough unless the page names an external relationship; never upgrade product availability into private-label/manufacturer proof.

Do not collect or quote phone numbers, emails, individual employee names, sales inquiry paths, quote/contact forms, rankings, recommendations, lead scores, procurement or sales strategy, compliance adequacy opinions, or private-label/manufacturer conclusions inferred from mere product availability.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the submitted supplier.
- The page must tie the submitted supplier, brand, division, or relevant site to South Africa through visible page text such as a South African site, facility, address, operating market, corporate registration, or named South African retail/channel context. URL shape alone is not enough.
- The page must tie the submitted supplier, brand, division, or relevant site to an in-scope bakery, baked-goods, confectionery, retail-fresh bakery, or ingredient-supply activity. A broad food-manufacturing claim without specific bakery/confectionery/ingredient relevance is not enough.
- The page must make its facet-appropriate source role visible. For `category_product`, use supplier-controlled product/range/facility/capability/spec evidence, not third-party profiles or certificates. For `food_safety_certification`, use certification/quality evidence that is primarily about certification status, policy, or scheme coverage. For `retail_presence`, use a source that names an external channel/customer/stockist/collaboration/private-label relationship.
- The page must expose a concrete source-supported finding for the declared facet. For `category_product`, the finding is a named product line, product family, ingredient form, application, or production capability tied to the submitted supplier. For `food_safety_certification`, the finding must explicitly name the certification, scheme, program, or certification status and tie it to the supplier/site/product range. For `retail_presence`, the finding must name the external counterparty or channel relationship at the strength actually shown by the source.
